The difference is what type of hormone (progesterone-only, or a combination of progesterone and estrogen) and in what dosage. Again, broadly speaking, the most ‚Äúmild‚Äù form would be a low-dose of progesterone-only. (Although I don‚Äôt know if they make the patch P-Only). A high-dose combination version will be the one with the MOST pronounced effects. The patch tends to have a lower dose‚Ä¶ but double check this. So it‚Äôs a bit of a spectrum, but broadly speaking, the side effects will be there to some degree no matter what if it‚Äôs hormonal. Hope that makes some sense.

This is your resting temperature (or basal temperature, more scientifically). At ovulation, a woman‚Äôs basal temperature rises. Other times, we use condoms. Boom. No side effects because I‚Äôm not taking anything. It‚Äôs awesome. No pregnancy so far! I did not know at the time that all these symptoms were most likely very temporary, and these were actually a normal withdrawal-like reaction my body was having.
